{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567349"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:59:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:59:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18963"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18963"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.94,0.01,0.04,0.01,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92819"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11697"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18963"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76178"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11406"},{"type":"tags","id":"11407"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27519"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27520"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92819"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department after a severe motor vehicle accident. She is unconscious with signs of internal bleeding and requires immediate surgery. No family members are present, and there is no advance care directive. Her condition is rapidly deteriorating.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate course of action regarding consent for emergency surgery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Proceed with life-saving surgery without consent","Wait for the patient to regain consciousness","Contact the hospital ethics committee","Search for an advance care directive","Delay surgery until family members arrive"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct action is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eproceed with life-saving surgery without consent\u003C/strong\u003E. When a patient lacks capacity and immediate treatment is necessary to save life or prevent serious harm, doctors can provide emergency treatment without consent under the guidance of state-based legal acts. For example, in South Australia, the Consent to Medical Treatment and Palliative Care Act 1995 allows medical practitioners to lawfully administer treatment when the patient is incapable of consenting and treatment is necessary to meet an imminent risk to life or health. Usually, a two doctor consent is required, with the opinion of the treating doctor supported by the written opinion of another medical practitioner who has personally examined the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are inappropriate because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelay surgery until family members arrive\u003C/strong\u003E - Any delay in providing life-saving treatment could result in the patient\u0027s death\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact the hospital ethics committee\u003C/strong\u003E - The urgency of the situation does not allow time for ethics consultation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESearch for an advance care directive\u003C/strong\u003E - While important, searching for documentation should not delay urgent life-saving treatment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWait for the patient to regain consciousness\u003C/strong\u003E - The patient\u0027s deteriorating condition requires immediate intervention\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the emergency is managed, full documentation of the clinical situation and decision-making process should be recorded. Family members should be informed as soon as possible. It is important to note that specific requirements may vary between states and territories, so practitioners should be familiar with the relevant legislation in their jurisdiction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In emergency situations where a patient lacks capacity and delay would lead to death, life-saving treatment can be provided without consent.","The principle of necessity allows doctors to act in the patient\u0027s best interests when immediate treatment is required to preserve life.","Documentation of clinical reasoning and decision-making is essential when providing emergency treatment without consent."],"references":["Office of the Public Advocate. Emergency treatment. [online]. n.d. [Cited 2025 Jan 21]. Available at: https://www.publicadvocate.vic.gov.au/medical-treatment/patient-consent/emergency-treatment","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx","South Australia Consent to Medical Treatment and Palliative Care Act 1995. Available at: https://www.legislation.sa.gov.au/__legislation/lz/c/a/consent%20to%20medical%20treatment%20and%20palliative%20care%20act%201995/current/1995.26.auth.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76178"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18963"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76178"},"attributes